P>Î±, fail to reject the null hypothesis.
Types of Tests:

Z-test: Used when the sample size is large (n > 30) and the population variance is known.
T-test: Used when the sample size is small (n â‰¤ 30) or the population variance is unknown.
ANOVA: Used to compare means across multiple groups.
Chi-square Test: Used for categorical data to assess the association between variables.
Scenario Example:
A basketball coach claims his team scores more than 50 points on average. To test this:

State the Hypotheses:

Hâ‚€: Î¼ = 50 (average score is 50)
Hâ‚: Î¼ > 50 (average score is greater than 50)
Collect Data:

Suppose the sample mean score from 5 games is 51.2.
Compare Sample Mean:

If the sample mean is greater than 50, it suggests supporting the coach's claim.
Decision:

Based on this simple comparison (without formal statistical testing), the evidence seems to support the coachâ€™s claim.
Applications:

A/B Testing: Testing two versions of a webpage to see which one performs better in terms of conversion rates.
Medicine: Testing the efficacy of a new drug against a placebo.
Inferential Statistics

Key Concepts:

Population and Sample:

Population: The entire group of interest.
Sample: A subset of the population used to draw conclusions about the population.
Estimation:

Point Estimation: Provides a single value estimate of a population parameter (e.g., sample mean as an estimate of the population mean).
Interval Estimation (Confidence Intervals): Provides a range of values within which the parameter is expected to lie, with a certain degree of confidence.
